      <ProgramInformation programId='crid://bbc.co.uk/3257009523'>
        <BasicDescription>
          <Title><![CDATA[Blue Note: A Story Of Modern Jazz]]></Title>
          <Synopsis length='short'><![CDATA[George Melly concludes the story of Blue Notes Records. A look at the label's current trailblazing artists, including Cassandra Wilson, Joe Lavano, Nora Jones, St Germain and Eric Truffaz.]]></Synopsis>
          <Synopsis length='long'><![CDATA[Blue Note Records epitomised cool. Even today the label's standards remain unsurpassed. Founded in New York City in 1939, the Blue Note catalogue is virtually a who's who of modern jazz - from Theolonius Monk and Bud Powell to Horace Silver, Art Blakey and the Jazz Messangers, John Coltrane and Miles Davis to Herbie Hancock, Wayne Shorter and Ornette Coleman. During its golden age in the 1950s and 60s, Blue Note released albums of such consistent quality they set the standard by which other jazz labels have been judged ever since - by musicians, critics and fans alike.

But the story of Blue Note is also the story of two men: Alfred Lion and Frank Wolff, two Berlin Jews who fled Nazi Germany to make a profession of their love for black music. They were the first to recognise the link between the design of a record cover, the quality of the sleeve notes and the music featured on it. They were also meticulous in every aspect of its production - using only the best vinyl, paying for rehearsals (unheard of at the time) and with engineer Rudy van Gelder, pioneering the distinctive Blue Note sound. 

In the 70s Blue Note transformed itself into the sharpest soul jazz label on the block (this is the first programme to look at the period in detail) - and it's still going strong today, at the forefront of the crossover between contemporary jazz, hip hop and soul. But the archive is second to none, encompassing some of the finest modern jazz recordings of the 20th century.

Programme 6
In tonight's final programme in the series George focuses on the labels current trailblazing artists - Cassandra Wilson, Joe Lovano, Nora Jones, St Germain and Eric Truffaz. The birth of Blue Note France, and where the New York division of the label is at - and heading - in 2002.]]></Synopsis>
